<br>
The entire airline industry was devastated for years (and is still reeling from the blow).  That it pursuaded people to stay away from that method of economic commerce for so long makes it an even bigger success.<br>
<br>
The economy of the entire nation was adversely affected much more so than if, say, a massive bomb had destroyed an entire army base.<br>
<br>
That people are now leery of doing business in large buildings means a further hit to the economy, since most large financial institutions are headquartered in large buildings.<br>
<br>
It was a direct attack upon the economic infrastructure of the US.  Warfare is the armed conflict between two economies.<br>
<br>
Causing long-lasting fear in the populace does not diminish the scale of the Act of War.  Instead, it dramatically increases it.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 2063<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/20/03 12:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=195.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Warfare vs Terrorism</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Destroying one of the biggest economic symbols of the wealthiest nation in the world had a massive impact upon the US economy. Much larger than the loss of two buildings and four airliners.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I can definitely see Anywon's point on this.  There is no question that 9/11 had massive economic effects.  The markets took a dive after 9/11 and still haven't really recovered.<br>
<br>
I'm not sure you can realistically call something a war if it's not a conflict between two (or more) sovereign nations.  I know we have the &quot;War on Drugs,&quot; the &quot;War on Terror,&quot; etc., but I think that such phrases are really propaganda.  I don't think of anything as being a war unless it's a conflict between nations, not groups of people.  Even in the Civil War, you had a secession which formed a 2nd nation and then there was a clear line separating the 2 sovereign entities.  Each party had an area of land that it controlled and a governmental structure that created and enforced laws over the entire civilian population in the region.<br>
<br>
When you have citizens of one nation attacking citizens of the same nation or another nation, without backing from a government, I don't think that's war.<br>
<br>
Maybe that should be part of how I define terrorism.  Unlike Anywon, I do believe there is a distinction between war and terrorism.  Trying to come up with a specific definition that works in every case is not easy.<br>
<br>
For example, if, during WW2, the Germans had bombed the Empire State Building and killed 3000 civilians, I wouldn't consider that an act of terrorism.  I would consider that an act of war.  What's the difference?  I think it's that Germany is a country.  Al Qaeda is not, it's just a bunch of nuts that have a mission that is not supported by any country.<br>
<br>
Ammelen <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/bvazaellecommunitycenter.showUserPublicProfile?gid=ammelen>Ammelen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I Live Here</span><br>  Posts: 2064<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/20/03 12:18 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=195.topic&index=44>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Warfare vs Terrorism</span><hr size=1> Merrahar-<br>
<br>
I find your argument completely unpersuasive.  You keep talking about the Israelis building fences and knocking down buildings.  At the same time, Hamas, supported by the Palestinians, is directly targeting innocent lives, not as collateral damage, but as the primary target.  In my mind this completely separates the two.  You can demolish 10,000 houses and it means less to me than targeting one innocent child.<br>
<br>
I can't prove Arafat's intentions.  Neither of us can.  No one but Arafat knows what is going on in his head.  All I can give is my impression.  I believe, having watched him over the years, that he does not seek compromise.  I think he is fundamentally a terrorist who will stop at nothing to achieve his end, that being the annihilation of Israel.  Like many others, I believe that there can be no peace so long as Arafat is in power.  Fortunately, he's getting old and won't be able to run things for that much longer.  Then I think we might have a real shot at peace.  I think Abbas had potential, but he needs to be more than a figurehead.<br>
<br>
As long as terrorist groups like Hamas continue to operate and enjoy widespread popular support from the Palestinian people, there will be no negotiations and no peace.  The Palestinians must shut them down to demonstrate that they want peace and that they can negotiate like reasonable people.<br>
<br>
